</note>
<note id="fs-id1163713269356" class="check-understanding">
<exercise id="fs-id1163713280602">
<problem id="fs-id1163713199341">
<para id="fs-id1163713487347"><emphasis effect="bold">Check Your Understanding</emphasis> Cut-off frequency for the photoelectric effect in some materials is <m:math><m:mrow><m:mn>8.0</m:mn><m:mspace width="0.2em"/><m:mo>×</m:mo><m:mspace width="0.2em"/><m:msup><m:mrow><m:mn>10</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>13</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup><m:mtext>Hz</m:mtext><m:mo>.</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math> When the incident light has a frequency of <m:math><m:mrow><m:mn>1.2</m:mn><m:mspace width="0.2em"/><m:mo>×</m:mo><m:mspace width="0.2em"/><m:msup><m:mrow><m:mn>10</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>14</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup><m:mtext>Hz</m:mtext><m:mo>,</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math> the stopping potential is measured as – 0.16 V. Estimate a value of Planck’s constant from these data (in units <m:math><m:mrow><m:mtext>J</m:mtext><m:mo>·</m:mo><m:mtext>s</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:math> and <m:math><m:mrow><m:mtext>eV</m:mtext><m:mo>·</m:mo><m:mtext>s</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:math>) and determine the percentage error of your estimation.</para>
