<exercise id="fs-id1163709668794">
<problem id="fs-id1163713120255">
<para id="fs-id1163713099793">Find the wavelength of radiation that can eject 2.00-eV electrons from calcium electrode. The work function for calcium is 2.71 eV. In what range is this radiation?</para>
</problem>
<solution id="fs-id1163713557747">
<para id="fs-id1163713066864">264 nm; UV</para>
</solution>
</exercise>
<exercise id="fs-id1163713259069">
<problem id="fs-id1163713424949">
<para id="fs-id1163713033129">Find the wavelength of radiation that can eject 0.10-eV electrons from potassium electrode. The work function for potassium is 2.24 eV. In what range is this radiation?</para>
</problem>
</exercise>
<exercise id="fs-id1163713297676">
<problem id="fs-id1163713067016">
<para id="fs-id1163709733170">Find the maximum velocity of photoelectrons ejected by an 80-nm radiation, if the work function of photoelectrode is 4.73 eV.</para>
</problem>
<solution id="fs-id1163713173374">
<para id="fs-id1163713082273"><m:math><m:mrow><m:mn>1.95</m:mn><m:mspace width="0.2em"/><m:mo>×</m:mo><m:mspace width="0.2em"/><m:msup><m:mrow><m:mn>10</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mn>6</m:mn></m:msup><m:mspace width="0.2em"/><m:mtext>m/s</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:math></para>
</solution>
</exercise>
